<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  webtheme's configuration should be able to load a <strong>palette from an external source</strong>.
  This topic grounds what "a palette" is across the industry, what standards exist, and how an import
  boundary should sit in front of webtheme's existing DTCG token model — the prep behind decision
  <a href="/backlog/1274-webtheme-palette-source-ingest-source-priority-static-only-v/">#1274</a> (the two
  forks carved from the <a href="/backlog/1252-webtheme-load-palette-from-external-source-palette-source-in/">#1252</a>
  build). It is <strong>not greenfield</strong>: the <code>webtheme</code> project (graduated from
  #364/#403/#404/#405) already adopts DTCG 2025.10 as its internal pivot, derives ramps from a seed
  natively, and compiles to native custom properties.
</p>

<h2>What webtheme already ships (the prior art is in-repo)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>DTCG 2025.10 as the internal pivot</strong> — <code>webtheme/tokens.ts</code> parses DTCG
    docs, resolves <code>{alias}</code> refs, deep-merges via <code>extends</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Native seed → ramp derivation</strong> — <code>webtheme/schemes.ts</code>
    (<code>deriveSchemeRuntime</code>, #405) derives a tonal accent scale from a single seed via the native
    relative-color syntax <code>oklch(from var(--color-accent) L c h)</code>, emitted <em>verbatim</em> so
    the scale re-tints at runtime when the seed token changes. The literal sRGB is computed in TS
    <em>only</em> to gate every step against <strong>WCAG 2.x</strong> ratio <em>and</em> <strong>APCA
    Lc</strong> — "lossy-but-loud, never a silent inaccessible token." A <code>curated</code> override
    supplies explicit per-step literals that bypass derivation (still validated).</li>
  <li><strong>No build-time baking</strong> — <code>webtheme/compile.ts</code> (#403/#404) compiles each
    resolved token to one custom property (typed numerics also register via <code>@property</code>);
    aliases compile to <code>var(--ref)</code> so values track at runtime. The file is explicit: "No
    build-time value baking beyond this; no second runtime."</li>
  <li>A Design Tokens protocol (<code>src/_data/protocols/design-tokens.json</code>), a pending
    theme-color intent, and a design-system bundle layer (#747) that could name an external palette
    source.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Doctrine in play: intents own the semantic tier (UX-only); webtheme owns primitive + component tiers; we
  coin no format — we adopt DTCG.
</p>

<h2>Standards landscape</h2>

<h3>1 · W3C DTCG (2025.10) — the interchange standard</h3>
<p>
  Reached first stable version (2025.10) on 2025-10-28, split into Format + Color modules. Plain JSON. A
  <strong>token</strong> = any object with <code>$value</code>; an object without it is a
  <strong>group</strong> (groups build the dotted namespace). Color is a <em>structured object</em> in
  2025.10 (hex is now only an optional fallback field):
</p>
<pre><code>{ "$type":"color", "$value": {
  "colorSpace":"oklch", "components":[0.62,0.19,256], "alpha":1, "hex":"#0d9488" } }</code></pre>
<p>
  <code>colorSpace</code> enum spans srgb…oklch…display-p3…rec2020. Aliasing via
  <code>"{color.blue.500}"</code>. <strong>A palette is just a group of color tokens; a ramp is a
  numeric-keyed sub-group — there is no dedicated palette/scale primitive.</strong> Caveat: structured-color
  interop is still maturing; many exporters still emit/ingest the legacy hex string.
</p>

<h3>2 · Native CSS substrate</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Custom Properties L1</strong> — flat inheritable namespace, untyped.</li>
  <li><strong><code>@property</code> (Houdini)</strong> — typed, animatable, validated tokens.</li>
  <li><strong>Color L4</strong> — <code>oklch()</code>/<code>oklab()</code>; oklch is the modern default
    for ramps (perceptually-uniform L).</li>
  <li><strong>Color L5</strong> — relative color <code>oklch(from var(--brand) 0.95 c h)</code> +
    <code>color-mix()</code>: generate a whole ramp from one base in pure CSS (parametric palette). This is
    exactly the technique <code>schemes.ts</code> emits. Cross-engine ~90%+, "newly available" — guard
    with <code>@supports</code>.</li>
  <li><strong><code>light-dark()</code> + <code>color-scheme</code></strong> — binary scheme switch
    honoring OS pref, no media query.</li>
</ul>

<h3>3 · Major design-system palette formats</h3>
<p>Three recurring shapes: (a) flat <code>family→{shade:hex}</code> map, (b) flat
  <code>--prefix-name-shade</code> CSS vars, (c) nested token tree with sets/themes/modes.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Material Design 3</strong> — HCT space (Tone == CIELAB L*, so tone→contrast is predictable).
    Seed → CorePalette → 6 tonal palettes → ~26 roles per light/dark. <strong>Generative</strong> — persist
    the seed.</li>
  <li><strong>Tailwind</strong> — <code>family × 50–950</code>. v4 is CSS-first
    (<code>@theme { --color-brand-500: oklch(...) }</code>; defaults ship OKLCH). Static swatches.</li>
  <li><strong>Adobe Leonardo</strong> — generative, contrast-driven: key colors + target contrast ratios +
    bg → swatches computed to hit each ratio. Persist inputs.</li>
  <li><strong>Radix Colors</strong> — static 12-step scales, each step a fixed UI role. Consume by role
    number, don't generate.</li>
  <li><strong>Open Color</strong> — 13 hues × 0–9, <strong>positional arrays</strong>
    (<code>blue[5]</code>) — positional, not shade-keyed.</li>
  <li><strong>Style Dictionary (Amazon)</strong> — the reference external-palette→theme pipeline:
    <code>source → per-source parser → token pivot → transforms → emit</code>. The architecture this
    boundary mirrors.</li>
  <li><strong>Tokens Studio / Figma</strong> — Tokens Studio JSON = token sets + a reserved
    <code>$themes</code> JSON. Figma Variables <strong>REST API</strong> differs: collections→modes→variables,
    COLOR = 0–1 float <code>{r,g,b,a}</code>, aliases = <code>{type:"VARIABLE_ALIAS",id}</code>. A
    <em>live, credential-holding network</em> source.</li>
</ul>

<h3>4 · Interchange / export-import formats</h3>
<p>
  Only JSON token formats (DTCG, Tokens Studio) round-trip scales + semantics + aliases. Binary swatch
  formats — <strong>ASE</strong> (Adobe, reverse-engineered, no official spec), <strong>ACO</strong>
  (Photoshop), <strong>GPL</strong> (GIMP, plain text, the simplest target) — are flat, lossy seeds: no
  scales, no semantics, no aliases, no alpha.
</p>

<h2>Classification — how the prior art settles the two carved forks</h2>
<p>
  Running the per-fork classification pass (which layer? · protocol or intent dimension? · open registry or
  locked set? · most-permissive default?) against this landscape answers most of the decision:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Layer = adapter, not protocol.</strong> Parsing a source shape into the DTCG pivot is a
    deterministic transform with <em>no swappable-vendor interop story</em> — so it is not a protocol
    (that would be lock-in for no gain). It is the ratified <em>adapter-as-normalization-hub</em>: ingest
    incumbents bottom-up into a lossy internal pivot the project never sees.</li>
  <li><strong>An open registry, not a mandated source set.</strong> Per Config-Extends-Platform-Default
    (cf. #370): a default-less registry of per-source parsers, projects register/extend them. WE mandates
    no fixed first-subset — so <em>"which sources first"</em> is build-order (backlog prioritization),
    not a design branch (#465: cost/sequencing is never a fork).</li>
  <li><strong>The genuine boundary call is file/snapshot vs. live client.</strong> File parsers
    (DTCG/Tailwind/M3-JSON/ASE/GPL) are pure local transforms → WE-layer. A live Figma Variables REST pull
    is network + credential → excluded from the WE standard per no-leakage + the #817 contract/impl
    placement test; WE owns the parser <em>contract</em> over the Figma Variables JSON shape, the live
    fetch stays product-layer (plateau's design-system creator already ships it, #889).</li>
  <li><strong>Generative ingest is nearly free, and must derive natively.</strong>
    <code>deriveSchemeRuntime</code> already derives ramps from a seed, so a generative source (M3 seed,
    Leonardo inputs) routes through it — "static-only" is reduced scope, not a merit end-state. A seed must
    derive the webtheme native in-cascade way; baking ramps to literal swatches at ingest violates the
    ratified #403/#405 native-no-baking invariant and loses the runtime-retint property.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Design implications for the build (#1252)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Pivot = DTCG color tokens</strong> — already webtheme's internal model.</li>
  <li><strong>Per-source parser</strong> normalizes incoming shapes into the pivot — mirrors Style
    Dictionary and the ratified adapter-as-normalization-hub pattern.</li>
  <li><strong>Value-type normalization at the boundary is mandatory</strong> — hex / ARGB int / 0–1 float
    / oklch; no two sources agree. Normalize to the DTCG structured color object.</li>
  <li><strong>Match on role/name, not position</strong> (M3 <code>--md-sys-color-*</code>, Radix step
    numbers, DTCG paths) — except Open Color (positional).</li>
  <li><strong>Lossy seeds</strong> (ASE/ACO/GPL) fill the primitive tier only; synthesize ramps + semantic
    aliases on top via the existing derive path.</li>
</ul>
